the prices are mostly a reflection of the emissions. so long-term, the sum will always be at or near 1, since the emissions (in terms of %) always sums to 1. dTAO is more about apr rather than price appreciation (relative to tao). the price will be chaotic in the short-term, but stabilizes over time near its emission %. and as root proportion decreases, the apr for subnet nominators increases. so the market value of your stake trends upwards if you're patient, and if the subnet performs well

one thing you could do for the subnets you're interested in is look at the price of the token in relation to its emissions. and see the premium (or discount)

e.g. for chutes the price is 0.138083 and emissions is 0.1265. so that's a ~9% premium relative to the "intrinsic" value of the subnet token. you could buy if you think the premium isn't that high. or you could wait for the price to fall even closer towards emissions. but also, it's possible for the emissions to change in the short-term as well. could increase or decrease. long-term, the two rates stabilize and end up very close

this idea above is also why it wasn't a good idea to buy when the sum of the prices was over 2, 3, etc. because if the price of chutes was 0.25, but its emissions still hovered around 12%, then the premium you paid for the token was ~108%. not worth it because the sum is not sustainable, and so you'll face heavy impermanent loss when the price falls towards the emissions

it's just my assumption. but yeah, I think I am right. imo subnets operate at their healthiest point when the price is close to emissions, as that keeps alpha_in per block close to 1. when the price gets too high, you end up having issues with liquidity, especially in the short-term

in the previous system, alpha_in was static no matter what. so when your price > emissions, the chain would start putting downward pressure on the price until it was equal with emissions. now that alpha_in changes when price > emissions, it's up to the market to dictate when and where the price will fall relative to emissions.

the sum won't always equal 1. it will just be really close to it, if that makes sense. so it will closely reflect emissions, but it doesn't have to be equal like in the older systems from the rao games

so long-term, a subnet might have an emission rate of 0.1, and a price of 0.11. you might have something like 110k tao and 1 million alpha in the pool. the injection pressure from the system isn't as strong as it was in the beginning. it's now there as passive buy pressure and to steadily increase liquidity in the pool. it becomes more and more difficult to push the price either way as a result. since it's harder to push the price, alpha_in becomes more stable. and the price stabilizes. what this also means is that if emissions were to somehow fall sharply (if the sum gets really high for example), this would not have a major effect on the price. the subnet would operate with little to no issues because of the sufficient liquidity.

tldr: the market pushes the prices down towards the emission rates because a high price relative to emissions is not sustainable. it lowers alpha_in per block which creates a liquidity crisis in the long run. over time, the price stays very close to emissions until it stabilizes. the sum always trends to 1 as a result.
